      text = "                          \
    Mirai Nikki is about Yuno. Regardless of any other plotlines that seem to be in the forefront, it is her circumstances that are in the center of what the series is about. The show focuses on the desperation that led to her destructive need for someone else to satisfy her desire for security, the mindless willingness to kill that resulted from the collapse of her mental stability, and the fragments of sanity that return to her periodically and at the last with the possibility of what she could have been, had she held on to her reason for just a bit longer.\
While Yuno’s condition leads\
          \
        to some nerve-wracking and amusing scenarios that are just fun to watch, her feelings, though extreme and fueled by madness, are not unnatural at all. Afraid of being alone and rejected because of her past, she latches onto someone who, in her mind, provides protection from emotional distress, and does all in her power to keep him by her side.\
Yuki doesn’t have one steady “character arc” throughout the series, and this is not necessarily a bad thing. He starts out weak and wimpy and he is aware of it, and his terror especially makes sense when he is suddenly faced with life and death situations. By the end of the series, he has not become a strong, confident person because of the extraordinary challenges. Throughout the series, there are moments when he finds his strength, but he doesn’t make a radical 180. He still makes foolish decisions like the young, spineless person he was from the start. He wavers between exploiting Yuno’s willingness to protect him, growing to love her for who she is in her moments of sanity, and finding the courage to be strong for her sake. Although he is never a completely independent person, which would be unlikely considering his disposition, his unhealthy dependence on Yuno becomes a more loving, natural one.\
As Mirai Nikki is almost wholly concerned with Yuno’s story, almost every development hinges on what she will do next, and the moments with the greatest amount of buildup and emotional investment are those in which she is the focus. The amount of time and effort they spend developing her character is an asset to the show, but the plot of the series gets neglected as a result and sometimes seems like nothing more than a wobbly framework for her story. The encounters with each contestant of the survival game struggle to carry any weight, as they are usually little more than a confrontation with a person who is crazy or evil just for the sake or it, or else has a melodramatic backstory and flimsy motivations. The course of the encounters sometimes provide circumstances to demonstrate some characteristic of Yuno or progress in her relationship with Yuki in some fashion, but more often than not they fail even to accomplish this and it just seems like poorly executed filler.\
The show feels rather like a thriller with so many close brushes with death, often at the hands of the cloying Yuno, and a halfhearted attempt at a horror series with some graphic, nauseating violence. The former works fairly well when Yuno is involved as her sweet, oblivious creepiness is as well-executed as every other aspect of her character, while the use of gore produces a reckless overindulgence in the barbaric that is more fun than disturbing.\
But for Yuno’s steady underlying plotline, the whole series is out of control for the most part, taking sudden, crazy twists and turns often due to the foolish decisions of the cast. Yuno’s abilities, too, though fueled by rushes of mad adrenaline and probably some prior experience, are mostly absurd. Depending on the mood of the viewer, these elements could seem either fun or messy, and the series does itself something of a disservice in taking itself a little too seriously throughout all these developments. Even so, the lack of moderation feels a bit liberating amidst the measured, aspiring realism in many anime.\
The opening and closing songs are not catchy or easy to listen to. They always feel on edge with way too many words and phrases struggling to find room for themselves, especially in the second OP, which is mostly Engrish with little meaning. This OP as a whole is an aimless mess and a stranger to timing. However, this is in contrast to the first OP’s perfectly synced, evocative imagery, and the second ED’s insightful focus on Yuno’s sorrowful mental state.\
Mirai Nikki’s soundtrack itself often creates a cool, devilish atmosphere with energetic synthesizers. But during many episodes some gorgeous instrumental piece will break through to indicate that amidst Mirai Nikki’s crazy, edgy exterior lurks a more sentimental story that gradually finds its way into the spotlight as the series progresses.\
Mirai Nikki’s graphics are crystal clear, with bold black outlines and solid, bright colors that prevent the kind of fluffy sheen that usually accompanies modern anime. The series retains an odd sort of artistic consistency with its regular use of overly loud colors, even if they do not blend particularly well with each other. Where the animation mostly struggles is in maintaining proportions as the characters change positions. Sometimes their legs look too small as they sit down or their heads look too big from certain perspectives. However, this awkwardness is rare and usually short-lived.\
The series’ facial designs are more proportionate than those of most anime. Although the eyes are still abnormally large, the characters’ faces are longer with larger, bolder noses and mouths to compensate. This makes them slightly less appealing in the customary anime sense and eliminates almost any traces of moe, giving the anime an impression of age it does not have. Yuki’s small, short facial design is the one that comes closest to disrupting this impression, singling him out from the others with the more childlike appearance befitting his vulnerability.\
Overall, Mirai Nikki is a rather messy series but that is part of what makes it so much fun, and amidst all the craziness is a somewhat bittersweet story of an unstable pair who slowly grow to love each other in truth despite their unhealthy mindsets.\
