                          \
    I’ve never watched Mirai Nikki in a literal way. The very first episode introduces the show as utterly absurd and in no way to be taken seriously. In one scene there’s a murder taking place by a psycho serial killer with the most blatant ‘this man is a serial killer’ character design you’ll ever see (stereotypical sorts of designs are used for most of the cast). In another scene, you’ll see the main character talking to a garishly rendered CGI God, and then he receives a cell phone that has access the future from God. \
Mirai Nikki throws so many ideas into the fray and\
          \
        lets them run wild without caring if they get out of hand. \
Story: 6/10\
To start I'll say Mirai Nikki's story is far from perfect, the author clearly took on more than he could handle without understanding his limits. Time travel, Gods, dozens of characters, clairvoyant cellphones, but that doesn't excuse the fact that he gets almost nothing right. However, due to the fact that this a battle royale story it is formulaic by nature and very comprehensible. So at the very least, you won't be confused. \
The story begins with an uncertain love between the wimpy protagonist Yuki Amano and the borderline insane Yuno Gasai begins to take a parasitic-like root, they're both thrusts into a survival game with 10 other contestants in which the last man standing will become the next God of the universe. Each contestant has access to the future via cell phone diaries which are each represented by a different quirk. Their journey to survive the vicious but vibrant battle royale is a thrilling and engaging one indeed. With a slew of wild and varying rivals to face off against, Yuki and Yuno do everything they can to survive, pushing themselves to the limit in the process. Yuno spends a lot of her screentime on trying to please Yuki while he fears her and cowers behind her while in combat. Her desire to become the center of his universe stems some viciously dark humor as well as tension; it's hard to feel a safeness for the characters while Yuno is onscreen. She's the most unpredictable wildcard out of all of the contestants. The fast pace keeps the show constantly engaging, never does the show drag on but it also has enough slow and personal moments to keep it from becoming breakneck. Constantly they jump from one vicious killer to the next, and as death is certain in a battle royale they never fight one for very long. \
Right from the first episode, the show makes no qualms about how ridiculous it is, it embraces the insanity wholeheartedly. Yuki and Yuno literally meet God and then kill their teacher who also happens to be a psychopathic serial killer. Although the story’s hammy it mostly is just a frame to set up the insane adventure without demanding much explanation for why the logic is so absurd, it’s a show about god giving a bunch of psychopaths cell phones that access to the future. \
Did people really expect Mirai Nikki to take itself seriously? I didn't and that's a big reason why I like it.\
Plenty of plot holes that appear especially towards the end of the series that are caused by the author putting the confused logic at the forefront of the story. On the subject of the show's ending, I can't say it's the best due to the conflicted logic, but in my opinion, it is a satisfying conclusion to the main characters’ arcs. The additional OVA, Redial, also adds a bit more to the ending by offering up more explanations and a satisfying recount of the supporting cast seen throughout the main story.\
While Mirai Nikki is enjoyable to laugh at its abundance of flaws, I would feel uncomfortable calling it so-bad-its good without it actually having some meaningful content. For me to consider a show as good trash would be a\
For each rival (or as the show calls them, “diary user”) Yuki and Yuno confront they change a bit, learning something from them and then moving on to the next. The breakneck speed at which the story shifts is what makes me call it dream-like, but the fact that those shifts are horrific and reflect some of my worst fears is what makes me call it a nightmare. Those fears are what you’d expect a teenager of the Yuki’s age to have. They’re extremely exaggerated in the show to be in keeping with the rest of the nightmare. But still, a fear is a fear and they can be applied to anyone who’s coming to terms with growing up. A few examples of the horrors; of losing your family and friends, being trapped in a toxic relationship, the finality of being married to someone you don’t love, having children… eeek, and most of all, of the future. There are a few more if you dig further, but the big one is really a fear of the future. \
What kid wouldn’t fear the future, becoming an adult? Not many at first, I know I didn’t until I saw how harsh life could be on my parents. Simply seeing adults as brave and all knowing is the ignorance we all start with. Once we see how harsh the world really is, we begin to understand growing up, you fear it. \
While I wouldn’t call Mirai Nikki strictly a coming of age story, it has elements of one tossed into the rest of the swill that makes up the story. \
Well, that’s enough sentimentality, for now, let's dive into the diary users.\
Characters: 8/10\
What the characters lack in depth the more than make up for with bombastic personalities and striking designs. \
What’s more is, they’re all assholes. Villians. You'll hate who they are and the things they do, but their overblown personalities are precisely what makes them so entertaining. They manipulate, they mercilessly kill, but their engagement comes from watching them grow and change. Despite having morals that you may not agree with, it is interesting to see them follow them diligently and try to explain away their madness. Each of the twelve contestants is granted a future diary that reflects an aspect of their background. For example; the main character’s diary logs everything he sees in the world around him because he’s a very passive person who chooses to observe rather than contribute. These personal diaries add an extra level to the characters, however, I felt like they didn't get explored enough; usually the diaries a little more than an excuse for some deus ex machina twists. \
Yuki and Yuno get the majority of the screen time, so if you’re not interested in them or the dynamics of their relationship then you’ll probably have a bad time. \
Their struggle to comprehend their feelings for each other feels realistic for people their age, even compounded with the struggle of the oncoming attacks from their merciless adversaries. \
Fans of this show seem to go nuts over Yuno and I don't really get why other than most of them are teenage boys looking for an anime lady to direct their hormones towards. As a character, she's fairly interesting for her yandere insanity, but just she lacks the depth necessary to be believable. I'd rather consider her to be an eldritch monster, a force of nature, that wouldn't be out of place in a nightmare. The disturbing ends she drives Yuki to are what makes her so scary, the ways she manipulates him and uses his weakness against him yet claims its all for love’s sake. There are people who treat their significant others like she treats Yuki, but obviously, their toxic relationship is much more exaggerated like everything else in the show. \
If you don't already fear being trapped in a toxic co-dependent relationship, then watch Mirai Nikki and you surely will. \
Most of the diary users are adults and their encounters with Yuki and Yuno reflect that theme of growing up and realize how harsh the world is. They’re all assholes do horrible things for their own selfish reasons. It’s almost hilarious how on point the author’s commentary on adults is when Yuki puts his trust in the police chief diary user expecting to be protected, then being disappointed. Then there’s Minene, the diary user who gets the most screen time apart from the two leads. She’s an adult who’s constantly reminded in her nightmares of the time when she first realized what the real world is like. And this nightmare is, of course, just as far-fetched as the rest of the show. \
It wouldn’t be Mirai Nikki without its patent absurdity! \
Notice how I never used the word 'believable' when describing the characters? Well yeah, that's because they aren't. Sure, some of the qualities they bear are similar to people, but they're distinctly inhuman. People might look down at me for saying this, but their unbelievability is intentional and necessary to the show. Well, the intentional part is definitely obvious. I mean really, just look at them. Their unbelievability only draws attention to what they are rather than who they are. After all, a bad dream is a bad dream. Even if they approach realism, in the end, they're anything but.\
[Audiovisual: 7.5/10]\
Kickass soundtrack. Also, the first op is one of the best ever made; loaded with irony and a fast-paced song that's equally edgy as it is thrilling. The second one is alright but as usual, it’s not nearly as good as the first. Both ending songs are great, they harshly set-in-stone the emotion that is evoked by each episodes cliff-hanger ending. The voice actors did a great job with wonderfully overdone performances, especially Yuno’s voice actress. Each character’s voice is incredibly exaggerated which only sells their insanity further. \
Despite being released in 2011 the visuals are relatively dated. The art varies in quality but is good during key moments. The use of color adds so much to hold your attention; the purples, blues, and especially reds are used the most to further exaggerate an already bewildering atmosphere. \
The characters all have varying designs that give you a sense of who they are or who they want to be perceived as before they even speak. Most of them are over-the-top and impossible to take seriously.\
Some of the slower scenes of just everyday activities between the action had lower animation quality. Usually, if the characters are far from the camera during action scenes Asread utilizes CGI characters, they look decent but that’s due to their distance and infrequent use. \
What saves the visuals the most is the direction. While I wouldn't call it masterclass, it gets the job done well enough. The action is well telegraphed so you understand what's happening and where it is. Plenty of scenes subtly use foreshadowing/symbolism to give you a nagging sense of fear for where the story will go.\
The director uses light (ie: sun) and dark (ie: shadows) to set the tone and indicate a tonal transition. For example, in one scene Yuki and Yuno walk down a hill away from the sunset into the gloomy night below. A scene like that does a great job at setting tone and foreshadowing. Scenes like this further reinforce my opinion that Mirai Nikki is good and is actually made with effort and a fair bit of talent.\
[Enjoyment: 10/10]\
Once it starts, it doesn't let up, not even for a moment. Pure insanity contrasted with the occasional quiet moment to show the audience that the characters are humans under their frightening personas. The director juggles comedy and the edgy action but doesn’t overlap them in an annoying or off-putting way. I think a lot of people saw Mirai Nikki and couldn’t decide what to make of its varying genres. Personally, it added a lot to keep me entertained, but I could see that aspect turning people off. Make sure to expect a comedy and a thriller before watching.\
Coincidentally, Mirai Nikki's greatest weaknesses—the overabundance of plot holes, continuity errors, and leaps in logic—also happen to be its greatest strengths. I always found it laughable when a vey obvious and story affecting hole appeared. Whether it be the future diaries either working better than the story set up in the beginning, or worse to fit the flow of a scene. \
Despite a few really awkward and sometimes tasteless (and totally skippable) nudity scenes that break the show’s crazy flow, it is a pure thrill ride of action and humor.  \
[Final Score: 8/10]\
What a thrill ride Mirai Nikki is. But there's more too it. Maybe I read into it more than the author intended, but that’s what I got out of it. You might too! But you have to be willing to approach it unbiasedly, with no expectations of how bad you may have heard it is. \
I hope my reasons for liking came across well enough. Thanks for reading!\
