    *SPOILER FREE REVIEW*\
Mirai Nikki is the perfect example of how dark themes does not necessarily correlate to a mature anime.\
Story 5/10\
Mirai Nikki conveniently used every dark theme out there in a bid to create a mature anime. They used gore, murder, rape and so on and so forth. The end result was an anime with a poorly executed edgy feel.\
The plot was interesting, and the pace was consistently fast. However, the first 15 or so episodes failed to feel deep and meaningful. The subsequent episodes were better as a neat plot twist was thrown in the mix. That being said, I really did enjoy the\
          \
        resolution episodes, as the ending was satisfactory and reasonable.\
Art 8/10\
The art was crisp and the animation smooth. No complaints here.\
Sound 7/10\
The OP and ED were both decent but not particularly memorable. The OST was pretty mixed. Some tracks really amplified the mood and suspense whilst others felt like generic B-grade horror film music.\
Character 8/10\
The series revolves around two seemingly star-crossed lovers, Yukiteru and Yuno.\
Yuno was already a complex character and the development played along nicely with her quirks.\
Yukiteru starts off as a spineless, boring character which would go on to make the same mistakes time and again. However, his development throughout the course of the anime was laudable.\
The supporting cast, especially the other diary owners, were handled nicely. It is interesting how some antagonists had somewhat justified reasons for their behaviour which shows the thought put into the back story of the characters, important or not.\
Enjoyment 7/10\
The pace was engaging and I enjoyed the whole series, the only con being Yukiteru's off-putting initial personality.\
Overall 7/10\
Although I disliked some aspects of Mirai Nikki, it is still an anime worth watching\
