                          \
    So, if you can suspend your disbelief and just enjoy the show, its actually a very rewarding experience. The first episode or so, I damn near dropped it, thinking it was going to be the typical fighting anime. \
Instead, it really fleshed out into one of the most addicting and \"page turning\" anime I've seen since Parasyte or Death Note. \
To preface this, my favorite anime are usually of the more serious/psychological type, ie, Psycho Pass, Ajin, Death Note, Parasyte, GiTS, Akira, Tokyo Ghoul, Broken Blade, Berserk, ect. ect. \
Once you get passed the first episode or so, the show starts to become a lot\
          \
        more like death note, were there are twists and turns. The best part, really, is the heroine, who is an anti-hero in the weirdest way possible.\
You can't help but root for her half the time, while the other half of you almost wants to kill her yourself. In that respect, the writing can be quite good, especially when they go into the backstories of each character (which they do, sometimes in detail.)\
Once the story gets going, there is practically no filler. The problem that most people have is that sometimes (alot) they stretch the foundations of time and space/ alternate reality/ the cell phones overarching technology. \
However, if you can overlook some of the more confused intricate details, this is a great show that will keep you watching episode after episode. \
The ending is pretty worth it, too. They definitely had enough of a story to fill all 26 odd episodes, so unlike alot of anime they didn't have to make false endings and patch the rest of the season together like, say, Sword Art. \
Its a fun, psychotic girlfriend, paranoia filled adventure of anti-heroes and heroines that is nothing if not original in its execution. \
Think Death Note if it took itself WAY less seriously, mixed with Battle Royale.\
