      text = "                          \
    What a godawfully ugly show this is.  \
I’m referring not only to the art style, which falls somewhere between unappealing and downright eerie, but to the show’s gestalt.  Nearly all of the characters are unlikable, except on a surface level, whether it’s due to their designs, their personalities, their actions, or the ideas they represent.  The show’s themes, when not actually alarming, are unsatisfying and demoralizing.  I’ve seen many worse instances of the “deathmatch between total strangers” concept, but I’ve also seen quite a few better versions.  The show is needlessly cruel to no effect other than annoyance.  The\
          \
        tone changes drastically with little warning and a total dearth of self-awareness.  Mirai Nikki may prove to be an enjoyable experience, depending on your tastes, but it is not a good show by any stretch of the imagination.\
Mirai Nikki leaves a very bitter taste in my mouth.  It has an uncomfortable, gloomy pall cast over it that derives not so much from the inexorable deaths of all the characters as from the implication that humanity is ugly, edgy, and stupid.  Not that people are flawed or imperfect and we should learn how to grow and change and deal with our problems, but that everyone is simply terrible in some way – pathetic, maniacal, greedy, vitriolic, deceitful, you name it – and that nobody can be bothered to do anything about it.  Time and time again Mirai Nikki has the chance to address profound moral questions: “Can good people do bad things?”  “Can all wrongdoings be forgiven?”  “What actions are morally acceptable to take in order to save a life?”  “How do I interact with someone who is personable but holds repugnant beliefs?”  Mirai Nikki has so many opportunities to pull itself out of the wasting hole of despair it has situated itself in, but acts like such considerations don’t even exist in its universe.  \
The show is bafflingly arbitrary in what it considers a forgivable offense.  One character can kill and/or maim countless bystanders but still wind up cast as one of the “good guys,” while another can turn out to be not quite as selfless and fun-loving as we had been led to believe and suddenly make public enemy number one.  You might view this as a chance to explore the complexities of human nature, but see the above paragraph.  It seems like Mirai Nikki wants to shove all this violence, gore, and despair down our throats so we’ll be impressed by how dark and brutal the show is, but then doesn’t want to deal with the consequences of having to explain or explore those traits in meaningful ways.  If stacks and stacks of (very recent) past misdeeds fail to sway characters in their assessments of those around them and don’t really have much effect on how people interact with each other, there seems to be no point to assigning such gratuitous violence to the show’s backdrop in the first place.  This show stacks bodies behind its characters not to provoke any deep thought or change the environment of the show or tell us anything new about the characters themselves; the only thing we get is an excuse for more gore at no real cost to the relatability of the characters.  Let’s not bother digging into how none of the kids seem traumatized by the fact that their homeroom teacher was a serial killer.  That little detail is forgotten as soon as it no longer becomes an immediate danger.  In fact, the world at large seems to be utterly oblivious to the enormous body count stacking up around the diary holders, but addressing that would take too much time and effort.\
Mirai Nikki truly suffers in the character department.  Yukiteru might be the most pathetic loser of an anime protagonist I’ve ever seen, and I’m counting Shinji Ikari twice.  I never sympathized with him, but found him as thoroughly unlikable as main characters come.  Yuno is kind of fun, simply because she’s frighteningly insane and the show manages to convey this pretty darn well.  When the show wants Yuno to unnerve the audience, she really pulls out all the stops.  That only applies to her dark side, however; the show keeps trying to push her cute, endearing side, which somebody seems to think exists, and while she may ultimately qualify as pitiable, lovable she is not.  Most of the other faces we see over the course of the show are forgettable, generic, frustrating, obnoxious, or poorly thought-out.  “Redeeming qualities” are largely nonexistent everywhere you look.\
That’s not to say that none of the characters endeared themselves to me, because over the course of the show I did grow somewhat fond of a few folks here and there (and by that I basically mean Minene and Nishijima, though Ai and Marco were all right, too), but nonetheless I don’t think too highly of the portrayal or presentation of those characters a lot of the time.  Mirai Nikki likes to think that it has some kind of “power of love” narrative wrapped up with thrilling mysteries, compelling character studies, and commentary on the deepest qualities of human nature, but most of the time it just sloppily barrels into incompetent repugnance.  Contrivances and plot conveniences abound.  One of the characters is literally called Deus X Machina.  I don’t know that that is supposed to mean anything (because it sure doesn’t in the context of the story, except to plant that phrase in your mind for the next time you see something happen for no reason).\
There are moments throughout the show that evoke genuine pity and sorrow, strike tangible horror, and inspire warmth – but only moments.  More often than not, the players stumble over each other in webs of dubious motivations, inconsistent characterization, and some of the unhealthiest relationships you’ve ever seen committed to animation.  Yuno’s homicidal obsession has made her the calling card of Mirai Nikki, the most recognizable character belonging to the yandere archetype, and the detail that initially interested me in the show, but Yuno by no means bears the sole responsibility for Mirai Nikki’s depravity.  The ways in which she interacts with Yukiteru seem to shift depending on conveniences of storytelling rather than following from any sort of consistent developments in personalities, and the same could really be said for every character.  The characters don’t grow or learn, not truly – they just “are” things one minute or episode and “are” different things the next.\
How many shows have we seen where a supposed villain turns out to be a decent person or is pursuing the same goals as the protagonists and joins their side?  I love it when that happens, but usually that character goes through some kind of arc or has strong reasons behind their actions.  In Mirai Nikki, the process we see is, “Eh, I don’t really care that you killed a hundred people last episode and then tried to kill me and my loved ones.  We’re pals now [citation needed].”\
The premise itself never quite gets the treatment it deserves.  The diaries are often used cleverly, but just as often it seems as though opportunities for development fell by the wayside.  Forget about receiving any sort of clarification as to the nature of divinity and the universe; the details of the “prize” for winning the game aren’t fleshed out enough to seem real, and even if the show returns to that plot point often enough to make it a tangible part of the series, enough important questions remain that it, too, becomes tiresome to think about.  \
After enduring so many episodes of pointless slaughter, ridiculously unrealistic characters, and too many dumbass twists to count, I was unreasonably satisfied with the ending, which is far better than what the show deserves.  I won’t share any details, of course, but the ending of Mirai Nikki was so strong that it took me aback.  I reconsidered my whole opinion of the show for a little while, and I’m even convinced that the show up to that point needed to double down on the ugly, ruthless, gratuitous, crushing insanity in order to allow the ending to have a real impact, and it did.  I hold this to be true, but at the end of the day, I had to sit through far too many episodes of that crap for one strong finale to make up for the rest of the shows failings, even those that are invalidated by the story’s end.\
It is possible to do all the things that Mirai Nikki tries to do and be all the things that it tries to be, but Mirai Nikki does not succeed.  It’s just sort of ugly and bizarre and steeped in moral turpitude.  At least my poor opinion of Future Diary follows the weighing of many factors both positive and negative; the show isn’t a complete wash, and I certainly don’t regret watching it.  In fact, when my irritation clicked off for brief periods, I even enjoyed it, and I would definitely be willing to give it a second chance at some point in the future.  The OPs and EDs are all pretty great, the performances are generally solid, and the premise is interesting enough.  For now, though, I still consider Mirai Nikki overall edgy, stupid, unsettling, and ugly.",
