    Never have I wanted to side with protagonists who couldn't be more crazy to do what they are doing. And yet, no matter how disturbing or weak our protagonists act, I easily forgive them or keep telling them to man up and get out there.\
I was recommended this anime and took no time in knowing what I was getting into...I thought it would be a cute romance. That's how much I knew. Turns out...I got a bit more than I bargained for. Episode 1 had me interested. Episode 3 had me needing to watch the rest immediately.\
There are some interesting strengths here. First (and not\
          \
        really a story) the idea of people working against each other with diaries from the future is very well executed. Yeah, the idea itself you can poke holes into, but don't be so uptight! No, I couldn't read something quick enough to dodge a bullet but that's not the point...it's gets a bit more complicated as situations present themselves. Our protagonists and anti-heroes Yuno and Yuki are not exactly typical of your high premise anime...\
*SPOILER ZONE BEGIN*\
What's interesting is you typically don't get protagonists that keep failing you and yet you want to root them on...Yuno is adorable...and completely psychotic. Then when she does something completely unforgivable, you forgive her because she's so cute...yet she's psychotic. Yuki is...well, a beta male loner that you wonder why you care so much that he should overlook all these terrible things. Then when he does, you wonder why can he accept it.\
*SPOILER ZONE END*\
That's what makes Mirai Nikki so compelling...everyone is doing awful things and yet everyone has a moment where you realize they are fighting for something. It puts you in a dilemma, not in a typical anti-hero sort of way, but more so...while you judge someone for the decisions they make, you can sit in judgement of yourself why you wonder why people aren't doing the amoral things you want them to do. \
Probably the main drive to the story is the continual turns (I am specifically not using twists here) to really punctuate the story. You learn straight from episode 3 that this will not unfold the way you will expect. And that makes getting to the end a curiosity which is the best anyone can ask for.\
Pros:\
Excellent pace for developing characters so you really understand their motivations in a rather simple premise. It makes the whole series more compelling to watch. \
Takes all 'adult' aspects very seriously. I enjoy fanservice, sure...but it can set a tone that would probably knock this show down a notch. It's not gratuitous with its use which just adds to the atmosphere. An appreciated respect. \
Cons:\
