    [440] = {
      score = 3,
      text = "                          \
    Mirai Nikki / Future Diary\
    Well, can’t say I wasn’t warned. I read the reviews. But let me tell you, I was not expecting this. For an 8/10 anime, this is easily one of the worst shows I’ve ever finished. Let’s jump right in, shall we?\
First thing’s first, what’s this show actually about? A bunch of crazy people trying to kill each other. A death game, essentially. At a glance, this show is almost like a character study, pitting different personalities against each other to see how they clash. The visuals are alright, if average, and the show is good\
          \
        sub and dub. So what went wrong?\
Pretty much everything, sadly. A big part of what ruins this show is the rating. I was expecting something far more potent and intelligent than what I got. I was expecting something like From the New World or Psycho-Pass season 1. The reality is that this show probably has less intelligence that the first season of Sword Art Online. Allow me to break it down for you. \
\
VISUALS [ 7/10 ]\
    A decent looking show, all things considered. Backgrounds aren’t totally barren, animation is smooth for the most part, although you’ll see some minor inconsistencies- this is another one of those shows where the close-ups look totally different than shots farther away. Future Diary is in no way perfect though. Character designs are shaky, with a lot of inconsistency that makes the anime look like it was made by two different teams. One team is solid and modern, with everything you’d want from an anime with a serious tone. The other is very vibrant, bright, and cartoony. Combine these two together, and you have the earliest warning to the show’s true nature later down the line. \
SETTING [ 6/10 ]\
    Our tale takes place in generic urban area, Japan. A combination of skyscrapers, business complexes and suburban sprawl make up the entirety of the show’s setting, with little in the way of creative or original ideas. Backgrounds are there, but don’t add much in the way of storytelling. This show knows how to set the tone, if nothing else. \
PLOT [ 5/10 ]\
    As stated earlier, this show is very much a death game. With a twist, however. Early on we find out that each of twelve participants possess a future diary, which takes on the form of whatever their original diary was written in. These diaries tell the future, and change accordingly when one of the diary holders changes the future. That is the basis of the game- kill everyone else while avoiding death yourself. The main tool used to accomplish this is, of course, their future diaries. The catch being that nothing unique is brought to the table here at all, other than the fact the participants in this game know the future. In addition, characters seemingly pull weapons out of thin air several times throughout the show, souring an already generic plot. Be prepared for a less than competent chain of events. \
CHARACTERS [ 2/10 ]\
    This is the biggest hit to the whole show right here. At a glance, Future Diary seems to have a unique and... quirky cast of characters. The further you get into the show, the worse the characterization gets, however. Yuki and Yuno, the show’s main pair, are rather inconsistent. Their best moments are often the ones that hurt the most, as both lead C’s get their screentime. With all that time to develop both Yuno and Yuki should be complex, multifaceted human beings with understandable motivatio- Okay, I’ll stop. Look, Future Diary has bad characterization, plain and simple. The entire supporting cast stays pretty much static for the entire show, but I’ll need spoilers to talk more on the supporting cast, so more on that later. Without giving too much away just yet, the cast is generic and disappointing both. You’ll figure out how each character pieces into the puzzle at a light pace. Future Diary will teach you what bad character development looks like, whether you wanted it or not. Absolutely no new ground is broken in this show. The characters themselves are either cardboard cutouts or are so inconsistent you couldn’t hope to figure out what their personalities are really like. Future Diary is definitely one of those ‘turn your brain off’ shows, so if you want competent storytelling, look elsewhere. \
PACING & PRODUCTION [ 4/10 ] \
    A well directed show... Right? Future Diary is alright- on the surface at least. The reality is much worse, to the point where it’s hard for me to explain exactly where the show takes a turn for the worst. Other reviewers describe this show as a trainwreck. Blunt, but accurate. But it’s fun to watch stuff explode. Well, take that clip of an exploding train, and hand the keyboard over to a monkey and you’ve got Future Diary. The pacing is random and disjointed. At the very start, the show seems promising as it seemingly finds its groove. About four episodes in, that groove has smoothed out and the marble just keeps on rolling. To who knows where, because the pacing sucks! Speaking Broadly, you’ll watch 2-3 episodes where crazy shit goes down, and then there will usually be an episode or two where it calms down a little, maybe introduces a character or two. And then back to the insanity, as the plot progresses rapidly and in a way where it’s hard to tell how much time has passed. The show straight up tells you the day and even the time quite often though, so don’t you worry about figuring anything out yourself. The show will handle it for you, which in the case of a thriller, is a very bad thing indeed. Be prepared for blatant stupidity, in addition to the already poor direction the show is taking. Without any further delay, it’s time to wrap review up in a nice little bow. \
STORY [ 2/10 ]\
    Time for spoiler territory. I’ll try to keep things vague, but read on if you want a complete review. If, after all this, you still want to watch the show, skip this section. \
    To truly understand the level of failure Future Diary delivers, you have to know about a few key twists. Which suck, by the way, just like the latter half of the show. My first major complaint is actually one regarding characters. I watched on FUNimation Now, so I saw the blu-ray version. Let me warn you all now; this show has obnoxious fan service scenes. Allow me to paint you a vivid picture from the show. A pair of youths fall in love at an early age, and spend a large chunk of both their lives casually dating. Eventually, this pisses a lot of their classmates off, be it from jealousy or just flat out hatred. Some girls arrange to set up the young love-struck lass, and she finds herself surrounded by thugs, who proceed to start molesting and raping her. The young lass is a girl named Ai, who really grew on me over time. Probably because she was my type, but enough of my personal attractions. Her boyfriend arrives just in time to stop the main course, and beats the hell out of all the thugs. Not before she gets thoroughly molested, however. At the end of this whole mess, the two lovers are sitting outside feeling sorry for themselves. Dudebro feels really bad that he left her side, and through some unrelatable, borderline retarded train of thought he decides he feels bad enough to kill himself. By stabbing himself in the neck with one of the thug knives. Girlfriend leaps over in time to stop him and they cry and be all sympathetic towards each other. There’s another catch, as if all I’ve described isn’t enough. Ai’s shirt got torn to shreds, and so the only thing on her top half is a jacket. When she leaps over to stop another teen suicide, the jacket falls off and camera makes a point of focusing very heavily on her chest. Amazing. Just what I wanted after watching this same cute girl almost get raped. It’s rare for Future Diary to use nudity, but when it does it’s always at the worst possible moment. Distracting, unbefitting and awkward, Future Diary demonstrates yet another part of anime production, and flawlessly shows us all how to do it wrong. \
    Oh yeah, and let’s not forget the scene where the show pervs on a pair of side character girls while they’re in a hot tub. \
    Anyways, let’s touch base on anything I have yet to mention. The gore. So this show has a strange bipolar personality- half the time it’s a goofy, colorful comedy that seems to almost be making fun of this type of normally very serious anime. The other half is, of course, incredibly violent and often gorey. Lots and lots of decapitation in this show, excessive and downright ridiculous death scenes, especially at the end, and an end body count that easily rivals most shows that are actually about war. Future Diary doesn’t know when enough is enough. The writers and directors were absolutely convinced that you just couldn’t get enough of the bloodshed, and so they just keep it coming. They kill off random characters left and right without taking the time to make us care at all, and often in outright stupid ways. They abuse not just fan service but outright nudity, and always with the worst timing humanly possible. The writers couldn’t even come close to salvaging this mess of a script, and no matter how much I think about it I have no idea how this show got the green light to be produced at all. Future Diary is a clusterfuck, through and through. It is the result of throwing a bunch of script writers and screenwriters in a burlap sack for three days straight, and then immediately producing whatever came out of that bag of cats, no matter how awful. \
    Future Diary truly is the perfect example of what bad anime is like, in every way possible. That really is the bottom line here, tragic as it may be. No amount of ‘But look at this!’ or ‘Hey, this particular moment was cool, right?!’ is going to make sitting through everything else worth it at all. The fantastic OP and EDs are the only thing keeping this show from being a 2/10. That’s enough ranting and raving for one review, I think it’s time for the bottom line. \
OVERALL [ 3/10 ]\
Tl;dr-\
Terrible story\
Awful characterization\
Generic Setting and plot\
Infrequent but intolerable fan service scenes\
Messy, half-baked script\
Inconsistent visuals\
And no redeeming qualities to speak of. Stay away from this beast, unless you really want to see what it looks like when a dreadful script curls up in a dark corner and dies. \
    For alternative options, look to Btooom! for your action/survival fix, hit up Danganronpa: The Animation if you’re a mystery/deathgame kinda guy, and go watch Fate/Zero if you want a good thriller/suspense series. Good luck and remember- You were warned!",
      helpful = 1,
