      text = "                          \
    Mirai Nikki TV (why is TV there anyway?), aka \"Future Diary\" is a psychological thriller. The anime's basic premise is about a god who gives a dozen players phones which can tell the future. They're ordered to kill each other and the last man standing will assume Deus Ex's place as God. The protagonist is Yuki, someone without friends and anti-social in general.\
The first episode blew me away. It moved quickly and smoothly. It gave us a strong premise. It had strong action and thrills without being mindless. Unique players and a mysterious cute girl determined to help Yuki. Finally, I thought to myself, I've\
          \
        found another masterpiece.\
Well, not quite.\
The story shows a lot of promise early on, yet shortly thereafter some scenarios play out poorly. Not necessarily in their outcome, but in design. More than once, you'll be asking yourself \"How did that happen? Is that even possible?\" It takes away the \"psychological\" part and just turns it into a thriller at times. Some scenes aren't explained clearly and there's even some jumping, making a few parts confusing. The main character is a whiney wimp for most of the story until the final part begins. This didn't bother as much at first- it's a tough situation he was put in, after all- I just wish he would have evolved as a character sooner than he did.\
Mind you, despite all of that I was able to thoroughly enjoy several aspects of the story and characters. Although some characters only last an episode or two and don't receive more than basic backstories, each character is uniquely designed and gifted with interesting diary powers. Yuno, the mysterious, psychotic, cute girl who aids the protagonist Yuki throughout will keep your eyes glued to the screen as you watch her decimate enemies with a knife, and outwit them with her cunning, even while you constantly question her motives and history. \
Action sequences are also a blast to watch despite the suspended disbelief, not due to the action itself but watching the people trying to overcome obstacles with a limited future-seeing ability (or even without it in some cases). And indeed, even despite predicting the final big twist (I got it in the right ballpark, anyway), I was left nearly speechless by it's ending. The story and characters managed to punch me in the gut enough to genuinely care about the outcome, something I can't say about many stories, plot problems or not.\
As already stated, the character design is fantastic, and art is well done throughout. Sound-wise, only one or two tracks stand out. The dub is good and I can recommend it. \
If you can look past some plot problems while stomaching the blood and gore, you'll have loads of fun. Enjoy the mystery, thrills, \"crazy\" romance, and unique characters (mostly Yuno). I give this one a hearty recommendation.\
        ",
      helpful = 1,
    },
