    [482] = {
      score = 7,
      text = "                          \
    Discussion:\
\"I laughed, I cried, I puked a little.\" Mirai Nikki is a thrill ride you'll never be able to get off of - whether you want to or not. Is it fun? Hell yes. Is it scary? Beyond belief. Is it sickening? Exquisitely. So if you enjoy rough turns and unexpected loops, disorienting corkscrews and dizzying helixes, then get on the Future Diary train. But if you're susceptible to any and all the things that make films R-rated, you might want to prepare yourself mentally first. This show will always take the laser to 11. If you aren't disturbed by this anime's content, then you\
          \
        probably aren't disturbed by anything at all. That being said, its enthusiasm in contriving absurd and thrilling scenes is so over the top that its plot becomes unrealistic and incomprehensible, and if you can't look past this fatal flaw, you won't enjoy the anime very much.\
Mirai Nikki's strongest quality by far is shock value. If you don't like being creeped out, don't even bother with this anime; it thrives on your discomfort. Without going into too much specific detail, I'll try and cover as many reasons as possible why it is so successful as a thriller. I'd tell you to expect the unexpected, but even with that mindset I found myself completely thrown off every single time a development in the story (or a scene) is made. Based on popular knowledge of the premise and the character Gasai Yuno, one is led to believe the anime would follow the direction of a generally comedic, cute, slice-of-life romance. Well, thirty seconds into the first episode would throw any expectations of that out the window. Even the synopsis on this very site explains that the story is a psychological thriller based on a psychic battle royale.\
But as soon as you think have a grip on what direction Mirai Nikki is going in, your expectations are instantly flipped. Battle royale doesn't even begin to explain the the series. Elements from many other genres, including slice-of-life, pop up extemporaneously throughout the anime. Zooming in, individual scenes are equally spontaneous and unpredictable. In fact, the one thing remains constant throughout the show is how quickly it can take a stunning turn in a matter of seconds. Between unexpected visual gags, vicious combat sequences, absurd gore, spontaneous nudity (usually clue-nudes), along with plot twists from hell, devastating backstories, and cringeworthy embarrassments, the series keeps you on your toes... and then makes you wonder if you still have toes.\
For all of that which works for Mirai Nikki, it can also be overwhelming. At times it's possible to become completely lost, due to the fact that there's very little consistency to the character of the show. While its capriciousness makes it fun and exciting, at the same it renders it almost unfollowable. There are episodes that make you wonder what the hell you're actually watching. Ecchi? Action? Romance? Shounen? Shoujo? The only consistently accurate answer is thriller. Even scenes which are entirely innocent and chipper on the surface are waiting to explode with spontaneous incredulity. The show is so erratic, it's not humanly possible to keep up with its behavior. Although Yuno is perhaps one of the better known examples of Yandere, I'd argue that the show itself is Yandere. Its juxtaposition of fan-service and bloody gore is almost incomprehensible. Does the mercurial nature of the series' storyline make it hard to follow? Often. But if you bear with the genre-hopping and general helter-skelter, the enjoyment reward is well worth the effort. A thriller at the core, this anime will keep your fingers clenched, spine chilled, blood curled, and eyes glued to the screen. \
I've gone on about its shock value enough, so I'll address the flip-side, which may detract from your enjoyment of the show. The show, for all of its whimsicality, is ultimately incredulous. Since many of the characters are literally insane, you have to suspend disbelief 90% of the time. This detracts from some of the more serious content by undermining its credibility. The characters' insanities are usually partially explained, but not to a degree which is satisfactory for a story that claims to take itself seriously. It would've benefitted considerably from more attention to detail with regards to its characters, and making them more believable would've helped it deal with the more serious subject matter. Some of the characters are explicitly archetypes or absurd exaggerations of such, while others have a single unique trait that carries their personality, which generally makes them seem somewhat shallow. There is one exception to this criticism: I found a certain diary holder (Minerva) to be by far the best-written character in the show. Since the reasons why are a minefield of spoilers, I won't go into detail. \
On the upside, there is at least one unique quirk for each of the entire cast of diary holders. What's most interesting is how this quirk determines their prophetic diary's abilities. For example, Yukiteru (the main character) has long kept a diary in which he wrote random events in, so naturally when it became endowed with foresight, it began prophesizing future events in his surroundings randomly, with its one exemption being his fatal weakness. Yuno is of course a highlight of the show, and although I felt her character was ultimately unfulfilled, her personality and her diary's powers are what drive the show towards insanity. I won't give spoilers, but the first three episodes should be enough to get grasp on how much fun she is. My personal favorite thing about the diary holders is their discreet parallels with the Roman gods of the Dii Consentes. Each has personality, history, or at least symbolism which goes along with their pantheon counterpart. In case you're wondering, in this review I'm referring to diary holders based on their equivalent deity to avoid spoilers - they aren't officially revealed in the anime, so it shouldn't be a problem unless you look it up on the wiki.\
The plot of the show is engaging enough, but definitely isn't one of its strong suits. I mean, at least it isn't shy about employing lazy writing - there is literally a character named Deus Ex Machina, after all. Divine intervention is consciously used way more times than necessary. The entire premise of the plot rests on will of a god to make it so. There is at least some motivation for Deus, but regardless, if there's a supreme being pulling the strings, the plot naturally loses dramatic tension. The flimsy plot construction gets even worse around the time you meet the equivalent of Dionysus, and you really have to wonder who would ever think it would be a good idea to give so many people power over the future and incentives to kill one another. The plot was fun and interesting, but to enjoy it, you have to forgive its flaws, which are pretty major.\
Fan-service tends to take over the plot more often than I would've liked, and I think it would've benefitted from making a decision to favor either fan-service or good writing. A lot of the show is 'just for fun', which would be totally fine by itself. However, it also seemed to overexert itself by trying to make everything fit into a neat and clean plot, after spending twenty-odd episode making it a mess. It suddenly takes itself very seriously, after having most aspects of the story be completely unrealistic. It's so incredible that it's hard to take the most dramatic aspects seriously. This weakened some of what was intended to be its strongest plot points towards the end of the series. That's not to say the ending was bad - in some regards it was amazing - but if failed to live up to the standards it set for itself in terms of conclusion because it didn't allow itself to make enough sense. It asks you to suspend disbelief at one point and then suddenly has you take everything for literal fact. I obviously can't specify what exactly bothered me about the ending, but often, the show tried to make the incredible credible, and although that has huge payoff when done successfully, it didn't work out because everything, from the characters, to the setting, to the storyline, felt contrived and unrealistic.\
Themes throughout the series were surprisingly well done. For a slasher thriller, that's a rare gem. The characters that were done well brought so much depth into the story, and even minor characters contributed meaningful vignettes. Loss of innocence is an elephantine theme throughout the series (well, what did you expect with serial killing middle schoolers), and Minerva gives one of the best soliloquies I have ever heard in an anime on the subject. Love is a strong theme, and it really isn't that surprisingly when you put together that Yuno is a phoneticization of Juno. Revenge and retribution is thoroughly explored throughout the story, leading to some very interesting character developments. The expectations for a boyfriend/girlfriend are reinforced by the story, but they aren't challenged or analyzed very much at all, which causes it to detract more than it added (or that's just my opinion, take it or leave it). Lastly, Sight, as a concept, is all over the place. Each holder's future sight, the things that their diaries let them watch over, as well as the entire stories of Yukiteru, Apollo, Pluto, Dionysus, and to a degree Minerva, all involve interesting symbolism, metaphorical value, and commentary about sight and seeing. Yuki's ultimate dream is symbolized by a telescope for crying out loud, and don't get me started on the quote: \"Suffering always comes from the unseen world.\" I was very impressed by all of the themes throughout the anime. Considering its strong suit is shock value, I suppose it's fitting that the theme's were so surprisingly well done.\
Verdict:\
Out of 100 points, because factors of 10 are easiest for grading.\
Plot - The plot was required to make the show as thrilling and shocking as it is, but insofar as the writing itself, it's pretty weak. It defeats the purpose to have everything be god's little game. Character motives were generally drawn for the purpose of making the plot move along, and because so many characters were unrealistic, they weakened the structure of the story. The plot wasn't bad, but it wasn't anything special, and the for the reason explained in the discussion above, it felt pretty contrived. 5 points.\
Characters - Whoa, the characters in this show. Literally every person is a crazy person in some way or another. If they aren't crazy, that just means they haven't broken yet. If you can suspend disbelief, their absurdity is actually lots of fun observe; however, if you ever have to do so, some of their depth is compromised. Most characters have good backstories, and everyone has a least a quirk or two to make them unique. However, some are more shallow and unfulfilled than I would've liked, and background characters tend to not make any sense at all. Still, the main cast is generally very interesting. I give it a 7 in character, with all positive attributes being interesting, and the main drawback being credibility.\
Emotional Investment - This series will get you emotionally invested enough. Yukiteru is a likable protagonist, though you'll have to forgive his wimpiness, and his motives are reconcilable. However, that's only the beginning, since there are many, many different characters that you'll end up empathizing with and feeling for, including almost every single diary holder. It's not the kind of show that's going to rip your heart out or anything, but it's at least fairly strong in this category. 7.\
Action - If it weren't contending with my previous review of Death Note this could easily be a 10. This show's action is so exhilarating that it's hard to compare to anything else. You'll be screaming on the inside multiple times an episode, and every time a certain diary holder touches an axe should make your blood freeze. Even in completely pacific scenes, spontaneous twists of circumstance keep the show exciting. But sometimes it really gets dragged down by fan-service and general silliness. The confrontations could've been made more epic, and some of the fights felt too easy. It's very strong in the action category, but it doesn't quite pass the bar of Death Note, so I give it a 9.\
Thought Provoking - It's not the kind of anime to make you ask the deeper questions, but it has its moments of insight. It's mentally scarring to a degree, and that's pretty thought provoking. There's not much to say without giving away major spoilers, so I'll give a 4 and leave it at that.\
Themes - There are very strong themes throughout the series, which is somewhat surprising, considering it's a thriller. Loss of innocence, love, sight, etc are discussed above, but there are many more present throughout. If you're curious, check it out for yourself. I give it a high score of 9.\
Emotional Direction - The amount of times I laughed out loud, yelped, cringed, tried not to scream and failed are tokens of how much emotional shock this anime presents. It has moments which are touching, creepy, and both at the same time. It can also be very depressing when it wants to be. If it were a little bit better written, this could've been a 10 category. However (and this is mostly due to the nature of a thriller) it felt pretty haphazard, and as a viewer I felt I was often being led to feel things just for the sake of feeling them. I'm going to give it an 8, mainly because of the looseness and almost randomness of its direction.\
Originality / Surprise Factor - The premise of a 12-team death match is not very original; however, the Psychic Hunger Games is at least something we haven't seen before. Some tropes and gags were imported from past anime. That being said, with all of the praise I've given the ability of this show to surprise you, it would just not be right to give it lower than a 9.\
Animation - The action scenes and gore are literally perfect. Many scenes had too much attention to fan-service, but other than that, they very well done. I think it could've benefitted from more detail at times, but it was overall pretty good. 8.\
Soundtrack - I had to go back to even notice it, but the background themes (and sounds) were used pretty well to build drama, hysteria, or intensity. While they're generally good, they're not outstanding, I don't feel like they're worth writing home about. On the other hand, both openings and endings were fantastic. The first opening theme has already become one of my favorites of all time. Of course, music is one of the categories most subject to opinion, so it's always to judge. I enjoyed a lot of music in the show, but it didn't stand out as amazing. I feel like I'm erring on the side of underselling it by giving a 7 - you might be like me and absolutely love it, or it might not suit your taste at all. \
That adds up to a cumulative score of 73. Always remember that I will be as critical as possible in my reviews, and keep in mind that 73 is not below average. (49 is below average.) Mirai Nikki has a lot of great things going for it, and so if you like to be surprised, you should check it out. If you are easily upset by R-rated images, err... I think there's a censored version. In any case, I hope this review was helpful for anyone deciding whether or not to take on the absurdly fun adventure in obscenity that is Mirai Nikki.\
