      text = "                          \
    (Spoiler-free) \"Maybe the future is bad. But there's a future beyond that, right?\"\
- Story: 3/10\
Well, all I can say is that the original potential of this anime is one of the only good points of its story. Battle Royale-style types of anime aren't that uncommon, but this one had a special twist that made it stand out: the future diaries. Twelve diary users are selected by Deus Ex Machina, God of the universe, to fight in a survival game to determine his successor. Using their own diaries, they can see into the future (albeit not without limits) and use this knowledge to either try and\
          \
        survive or hunt down their fellow competitors. Makes for a promising story, right? \
... Well, it does. But that's not what we get. \
My main problem with Mirai Nikki is that it's too focused on dropping \"OH SHIT\" moments on the viewer, rather than actually trying to develop its characters. If you are somewhat squeamish with blood and gore, I do not recommend this anime to you UNLESS you go out of your way to watch the censored version. However, the censored version still has a good amount of blood in it, but without as much gore and brief nudity. Yes, this anime has that, too. Also, there are rape and suicide triggers, so be careful with that. \
 Going back to the whole thing with the show trying to pull the rug out from under you ALL THE TIME, it gets annoying but it also makes the show fun to watch. After I got past my initial annoyance, I went into the next episodes thinking, \"Lol I wonder what shit's gonna go down this time.\" This is what made Mirai Nikki entertaining for me, and what made me keep wanting to watch it. Admittedly, near the end they drop a crap ton of mindfuck bombs on us that make the story take a 180 and next to nothing makes any coherent sense anymore. Characters are able to do stuff that they shouldn't be able to do just because it looks cool and badass and whatnot. \
And then there's the ending.\
I won't spoil anything about the ending since this review is spoiler-free, but all I'll say is this: It did tie up some loose ends and gave a sense of closure, but it was incredibly anticlimactic. They later try to resolve this with the OVA, Redial, which I feel gives a better ending to story but is still ridiculous in itself. \
Overall, the story had great potential, but fell short because of three reasons: 1) the characters, which I will go into later, 2) the focus being on pulling the rug out from under the viewers, rather than creating a consistent and meaningful story and developing the characters, and 3) using shock value as a means to make the actions of a character stand out WAY TOO MUCH. \
-Art: 5/10 \
The art style is meh, I honestly just don't like the way their noses look. Other than that, though, it gets the job done and actually depicts the blood and gore well. It's fairly consistent, although there are some derpy shots at times. Some of the effects were cheesy and made me cringe. Character design was fine, everyone was distinctive and their outfits and whatnot fit their personalities. \
The first opening is gold both visually and audio-wise, although I'll only mention the visual of it here. The opening is pretty much just black and white with only red highlighted, accenting the blood and the red sky depicted, which helps give the creepy and psycho feel of the show. It's great. If you decide not to watch the show, at least watch the opening. \
The first ending is pretty good. Visually, it's pretty simple with the diary users just fading from their scenes and showing a few other shots of of Yuki, Yuno, and Akise, but it fits the mood of the show. The first 16 seconds is my favorite part, personally. \
The second opening isn't as good as the first, and instead of highlighting red, everything has a blue tone. It also reuses some of the animations of Yuno from the first opening, but they don't seem to fit as well. Everything else is meh.\
The second ending is nothing special. It's literally just a bunch of shots of Yuno. \
- Sound: 7/10\
I actually like the Mirai Nikki OST. The BGM ranges from happy and calm to creepy and dark. It's not noteworthy or epic, but none of the music sounds out of place and gets the job done. The sound effects were good and didn't sound too unrealistic. \
Onto the seiyuus/voice actors. The seiyuus in Mirai Nikki did a good job, namely Yuno's. I doubt any English voice actor can do Yuno's voice as it was done in the Japanese version. This is one of the main reasons that a lot of people hate the dub. Yuno's high-pitched, creepy, and at times psycho-sounding voice wasn't present in the English dub. I've also heard the argument that Brina Palencia (Yuno's English VA) makes Yuno sound a lot older than she actually is and doesn't make her sound like a total psycho bitch. I agree in the sense that the Japanese voice of Yuno is better because it makes her sound like a creepy little girl, but I also believe that her English voice actor is not as shitty as everyone says. Like I said earlier, I doubt there are very many VAs who can pull off doing a voice exactly like Yuno's Japanese voice comfortably for twenty episodes on end. Most high-pitched female voices in anime are used to make the character sound cute, not creepy. A lot of English VAs can pull off the cute, but not the creepy. The solution? Drop the pitch but keep the creepy vibe. Did Brina Palencia do that? Yes, but not well enough. Her voice just isn't suited for it. This is the fault of the casting. \
Anyways, the dub itself was meh. The script was cheesy at times and made the story sound a lot more dramatic than it actually was. The voice actors did a decent job, but it's more a problem of casting. Like I stated before, Brina Palencia's voice just wasn't suited for a character like Yuno. I had the same problem with Yuki's English VA. He did a great job, but like with Yuno's VA, his voice made him sound like an older teenager (16-18) even though he's actually 14. I don't recommend the dub unless you're too lazy to read subtitles and don't mind the older-sounding voices. \
The only reason I'm giving sound a 7 is because of the first opening (and ending, but mainly the opening). If you have never seen it, GO WATCH IT. The music is epic and the visuals compliment it excellently. It's easily one of the best anime openings I've ever seen. \
The first ending is also catchy and sets the mood well, but isn't as epic as the opening. I still like it, though.\
The second opening and second ending are passable, but I prefer the first opening and ending far more. The second opening is sung in Engrish, but I honestly couldn't tell at first until I saw a version with subtitles. The second ending is meh. \
- Characters: 2/10\
Ugh. Given better characters, this could have been a great story. The two main characters, Yuki and Yuno, would have worked as characters if they weren't the MAIN leads. If they were just some random side characters, or even diary users with a minor role, them being in the story would be acceptable. Unfortunately though, they were placed in the main character slot, meaning we see the story through their perspective (mainly through Yuki's, though). \
Starting off with Yukiteru Amano, aka Yuki, he's an average 14 year old, but has no friends. As a result, he spends all his time on his phone (not unlike most teenagers nowadays). Not too bad of a character background, but my main problem with him is that he's a total wuss and can't get anything done himself. Seventh, aka Marco Ikusaba, another diary user, even calls him out for this in the show, which means the script writers intentionally made him to be a scared little kid who can't do anything without Yuno, who acts as his plot armor. This changes later near the end of the show, but not in a pleasant way. \
Now, onto the Yandere Goddess of anime herself, Yuno Gasai. At first we see her as a popular, smart, pretty, and sweet girl who has a slightly obsessive crush on Yuki. As the story progresses, however, she switches between this personality and the crazy yandere stalker who is completely obsessed with Yuki and basically forces him into a relationship. When people \"threaten her man\" in any way or try to hurt him, she goes psycho bitch on them and kills them. Literally. Also, whenever any female interacts with Yuki in any way, it becomes Yuno's new task to kill her. Honestly, about 90% of the blood spilled in the whole show is because of Yuno. And that's saying a lot. \
Now, the \"romance\" between the two is once of the focal points of the show, and... I'm kind of hesitant to even call it \"romance\". Yuno's obviously infatuated with Yuki to the point where she feels like her life would be nothing without him. To this end, she protects Yuki from the other diary users in order to keep him from dying. Her diary is literally called the \"Yukiteru Diary\" (or the \"Diary of Future Love\", as she likes to call it), and she gets to see entries about his future in ten-minute intervals. Now, when I said she protects Yuki from the other diary users, it makes her sound like a good girlfriend, right? I mean, who doesn't want a girlfriend/boyfriend who'll protect you when your life's in danger? While it's true that Yuno does protect Yuki, she also goes a little... Extra. A lot extra, actually. A girl invited Yuki to hang out after school? SLICE THE WHORE'S NECK OPEN. After visiting Yuki's house, she said she was glad Yuki's mom took their \"relationship\" well, because if she didn't, things would have \"gotten ugly\". I know it's a common trope for a girl to have a bad relationship with her mother-in-law, but killing your boyfriend's mom because she doesn't approve of your relationship with him? And that's just scratching the surface of her yandere-ness. \
Now, Yuki knows that Yuno's a psycho mass-murdering yandere. Why does he keep her around? Because he knows that without her, another diary user's gonna come and take him out. He doesn't want to die. But he doesn't want to fight, either. He's reluctant to get his hands dirty. So he lets Yuno take care of that. Their relationship is give-and-take. \"Alright, if you protect me, I'll let you hang around me and you'll get the occasional kiss.\" Yuno knows he's just using her, too, but she doesn't care; as long as she gets to be with him, it doesn't matter. The only time they actually start to act like a real couple is near the end, but then SHIT GOES DOWN and the rest is spoiler territory. Their relationship is like trying to make a smoothie by putting rocks in a blender along with some fruit and ice cream and expecting something good to come out of it. You can try to sweeten up their relationship with the occasional kiss and cheesy lines, but it doesn't change the fact that their \"romance\" is a huge mess. \
It should go without saying that they do some things that fourteen year olds shouldn't be doing. In other words, everything they do in the whole show. \
The minor characters aren't as bad as Yuki and Yuno. Some of them I actually liked. But they don't make the story better than it actually was. If anything, they're just plot devices used to try and develop Yuki and Yuno's relationship. This wouldn't be a problem IF YUKI AND YUNO ACTUALLY DEVELOPED AS CHARACTERS. Develop the characters well, and their relationship will develop too. Mirai Nikki does the opposite and tries to develop their relationship without actually developing the characters themselves. This is the the primary reason that Mirai Nikki failed story-wise.\
- Enjoyment: 7/10\
I gave a pretty negative review, so why am I saying I enjoyed it? Because even though it sucks as a show, it's still fun to watch, and that's the whole reason I watch anime. If you like watching anime to watch brilliant masterpieces with wonderful characters and interesting and developed storylines, you are most certainly going to hate this anime and should stay away. But if you like watching anime for sheer entertainment value, Mirai Nikki might be worth a watch, if you don't mind blood, gore, and brief nudity (although it is toned down in the censored version). It does a good job of keeping you in suspense and keeping you on the edge of your seat, though the story falls flat on its face because of its disappointingly flat characters  and its ending is lackluster, to say the least. \
