    Very polarizing anime, and it's not hard to see why. Mirai Nikki is an anime suffering from genre identity crisis, poorly written periphery characters, and a plethora of plotholes. That tends to lead people to hate it....... Except for the people who are so completely wooed by the show's legendary female lead that they're willing to disregard the series' problems.\
\
Where do I stand? Well somewhere in the middle. I think that, by and large, Mirai Nikki had vast potential that it squandered horribly. The anime is guilty of careless attention to detail, time and time again. But I can't bring myself to rate it as\
          \
        terrible because I know I'd be lying if I said there weren't times I got exceptionally invested........ Let's try a detailed breakdown. \
Story: 4/10\
For starters, it's just.... so full of plot holes guys. Not to mention the pacing problem: Mirai Nikki's arcs mostly last about two episodes usually. In other words, the antagonists are dispelled shortly after being introduced. As a result character development is practically nonexistent, and the suspenseful setups we get are typically resolved in disappointing ways that are often the worst possible combination of boring and prepesterous.\
In general, things are left unexplained, and NOT in a fun ambiguous way, but rather a \"Wow, this writing is lazy as fuck\" way. So much about virtually every major event in this series simply doesn't make any sense at all. Police are exceptionally incompetent, character motives turn on dimes without explanation, settings aren't handled with care..... It's a freaking mess. \
It's also worth pointing out that the OVA is, for whatever reason, actually a vital part of the story (and was the actual ending to the manga). While I personally like the OVA's ending (one of the story's few redeeming qualities), I'm unclear as to why it wasn't simply included in the final episode.\
In summary, what saves the story from being a total disaster is a well-executed endgame. It's just too bad that this does nothing to keep you from shaking your head at the finer details of the show, especially in the beginning as a first time viewer. Mirai Nikki simply didn't seem to care much about details, and it's noticeable and bothersome.\
\
Art: 7/10\
Mirai Nikki is mostly well-drawn and well-animated. Nothing is groundbreaking, and a few characters look odd, but the styling is consistent and at no point a real liability in any way. \
Sound: 6/10\
Meh. Some of the effects are odd, but my main issue is the music. While the piano tones can be effectively haunting, they're a bit overdone, and some pieces are just straight up cheesy. Furthermore the second opening and second endings both come off as being very lazily done. Still, there's no glaring awfulness I suppose\
Character: 6.5/10\
Yuno Gasai brings this score up significantly by being a near 10 herself. I will say that [slight spoiler in the remainder of this sentence] her character gets in my opinion a bit cheapened at the end of the story by some weird revelations, but she's still exceptionally fun to watch and shockingly lovable for such a dark individual. \
What's absurd to me, then, is how the same writer who put so much care into writing Yuno Gasai could be so UTTERLY CARELESS when writing just about everyone else. \
Our male protagonist, Yukki, is often horribly inconsistent. He will inexplicably make 90, 180, or even fucking 360 degree turns at random. It's bizarre and makes him hard to empathize with. How are we supposed to get behind a character whose motives we really just don't understand? Granted he comes around and is somewhat charismatic at the end, but it's not enough to forget how bothersome he was before. Much like with the story, Yukki is well-done in terms of the \"big picture\" but just so awfully done in the little details that it's hard to ignore. \
Most other characters are flat as pancakes and only half as interesting. Occasionally we run into some fairly interesting folks, but the thing is that these type of characters are still only 7s at best, and for every one of them is three 2's screwing everything up.\
In summary, if not for Yuno, I would have given this a character score of 3/10.\
Enjoyment: 7/10\
For a long time I was willing to mostly look past all of the plot silliness and character issues because I got invested in a more simple aspect of the show that was mostly handled with great care [SPOILER AHEAD]: the romance. I watched because I wanted to see what happened between Yuno and Yukki and I felt I would have a strong reaction. But the ending really only left me scratching my head in a bit of confusion. I'm not sure how I feel, and to me that's not good in the world of entertainment. Still, I'd be lying if I said I didn't have fun watching Yuno go apeshit throughout most of this. But for every Yuno-is-awesome moment, there was a moment of Yukki godawfulness or annoyance at details that honestly I can't say didn't screw with my enjoyment a bit. \
\
Overall: 6/10\
Is Mirai Nikki worth your time? Well, that depends: what are you expecting? If your'e expecting an all-around solid show that handles plot, characters, and everything else with care and attention to detail, you'll be massively disappointed. Mirai Nikki, simply put, is not a show which pays careful attention to detail. Plot holes dominate, and so much is left unexplored, unexplained, or simply unjustified. \
But if you're looking at this show primarily because you want to see what all the Yuno Gasai fuss is all about? Well then maybe you'll find that it is, in some way, worth your time. I'd be lying if I said Yuno Gasai hasn't earned her place as one of my all-time favorite characters........ She could've been done better, imo, but so much of her is done so well. \
My guess as to why this anime tends to attract a slew of both strongly negative and stronglypositive reviews is that, essentially, its viewers can be divided into two groups: Those who felt Yuno Gasai lived up to the hype and those who either didn't or didn't think it was enough.\
If you DO decide to watch this, be sure to catch the OVA after you're finished. To not watch it is to not get the answers to the questions you'll have.\
