    [506] = {
      score = 6,
      text = "                          \
    Very minor spoilers.\
It's my second review and I can already feel myself becoming a jaded anime guy. Yikes. Let's get into it.\
Mirai Nikki is really popular on this site, so I'm assuming there's some kind of cult following but that's not really what this is about. We grade on merit only, baby.\
When I review, I like to see how well a show reaches the audience's ideal version of the show. What is the ideal version of MN? I'm not really that sure. I think it would be very gruesome (R-rated level), have a lot of twists, and be thought-provoking to some level. MN is mostly\
          \
        a thriller, and it seems like it wants to have drama and action elements mixed in. It only accomplishes this mix-in to limited success. What it boils down to is that most of the production attributes don't allow MN to really be what it wants. If MN were what it wanted to be, it would be really good. There are a bunch of good ideas and missed opportunities in here, but they don't get fleshed out enough, for various reasons.\
\
Story: 6\
Real quick, you have a bunch of people who get diaries of a certain aspect of the future. They play last-man-standing, and the winner becomes the god of time and space.\
While watching, I was very bored with the story for a while. For a greater chunk of the story, the plot is just about fighting through a gauntlet of diary users as they each try to kill Yukki and Yuna. I found this phase to be just... really boring. There's not much going on. It's the beginning and I can understand that being very slow. It helps you ground yourself in the world. But nothing new is happening. You get used to Yuna being crazy a few episodes in (or at least you think you do). That's all these episodes accomplish. There's no character growth. It's not really action-focused. There's no interesting interplay between diary users. There's no forward momentum, to feel like they're scaling up to fight a big boss. It just feels like they're setting the stage of the story but it is really taking too long. \
When Yuna and Yukki finish fighting the 7ths, the plot starts to ramp up. Characters start getting developed a bit, mysteries surrounding Yuna get brought into the spotlight, and the bigger questions regarding the end of the survival game get murkier. Once this happened, I took a liking to the series. It's interesting because the reminds me exactly of my experience with Fullmetal Alchemist: Brotherhood. I was very bored for the first 40ish episodes, but once we reached the final act I was on the edge of my seat seeing the various conclusions for each group of characters. MN doesn't succeed nearly as well as FMA: B, but it's the same idea.\
From here, we see dramatic changes in our characters and get more exposed to the background of Yuna, until we reach the real final act. The real final act is more supernatural than the rest of the show is, but I think it's a totally fine ending. There are a reasonable amount of questionable plot developments (they don't call him Deus Ex Machina for nothing), but none of them are that bad. I think if you're willing to jab at a show for minor plot inconsistencies, you already don't like the show for other reasons (unless the plot inconsistencies are fueled by character inconsistencies, then you're in the clear). The pace picks up a lot from here, and it's sort of a mad dash to the finish line. Yuna reveals a lot about herself and her motives. There isn't much time to meditate on that, and that's OK. \
Overall, I think the plot could use a little trimming. The first half of the show is slow and the few plot points that are generated here can probably be boiled down by reducing the number of diary users and maybe squishing a few unnecessary characters together. The latter half was 'good'. The whole thing is 'fair'. In an ideal MN world, you'd want to see more action, more diary interplay, or more character development in the first act.\
\
Art: 6\
I don't think the art is really that bad, but it doesn't serve the ideal MN experience. Let's start general. Some of the CGI is annoying. The modeling is often unrefined. I'm a stickler for models that don't look like they fit in well enough. Character drawings get really lazy if they are far away from the camera. Looks very sloppy. Character design is... sometimes stale, but generally good. Sometimes characters just look bizzare and have poor proportions/angles. \
Furthermore, I don't think the style supposed what MN wants to be. A big thing with MN should be gruesome, impactful, scenic violence. Tarantino-type stuff. The action isn't fast, but you want to feel it. Firstly, blood in this series is pretty poorly done. Most of the time it looks like dark-red smudges. I want to see satisfying, gruesomely red blood. Make me feel it. Same thing with the knives. There are so many slicing objects in here and they don't really shine. Animating metal like that can be tricky, but it is worth it. It makes a huge difference. A super cartoony knife just doesn't feel like a knife, it lacks the proper lighting and angles to really believe it. Also in general, the style is pretty bubbly and doesn't use shadows and dynamically as it should. A dynamic art style, like the kind you see in One Punch Man, does wonders to set the tone of the scene. When MN tries to be a thriller, I want to see dark shadows and contrast, dramatic cuts, and disturbing detail. When it's action, I want to see fast-paced tracking shots and crazy motion blur. It matters. MN goes too bubbly, for a style which is totally average for anime. But that's not what's best for MN. \
\
Sound: 7\
OP1 and ED1 are good. ED2 is fantastic. OP2 is weird and in English with heavy accent, not sure how I feel about it. The score pieces are hit and miss. Some are pretty good, others are pretty awful. My least favorite part is the screams in this series. And there's a lot of them. Anime screams are a big deal because they are easy to do sooo poorly. They're bad in this. They need to be good. It's a thriller! That's all. Everything else is totally average from what I can tell.\
\
\
Character: 7\
I was going to give this like a 4 but many of the longstanding characters redeemed themselves by the end. In the gauntlet phase of the plot, nearly all characters are forgettable, since they don't impact Yuna or Yukki in any meaningful way. There are some decent character moments though. 12th, 7thM, and Kousaki all have some pretty funny/unique scenes, which I think more of these background characters could do with. A different show that does this well is My Hero Academia do this well. But really, Yukki's friends and a majority of the diary holders are super, super bland. 7thM and Minene (and Nishijima, I kind of count him as part of her character) and pretty decent characters that feel like the impact Yukki. The rest of the side characters are worthless. \
Yukki starts off super annoying. He starts getting involved with 11th, his personality dramatically changes, and for good reason. He turns into just one of those I'm-a-heartless-know-it-all main characters, which sucks, but then he softens up again so it's OK. During the final act, he has to do a lot of shit, and his character gets put to the test. In the end, he ends up being a pretty decent character. I just wish he would shut up about stargazing. Seriously, that hook got so old. Something that I resonate with is that when Yuna tells him why he loves her, he doesn't put up a fight at all. It seems like he accepts it. But even waaaayyy later, he is only thinking about her. Even if what they had shouldn't be unique. To me, that's pretty relatable. Them's some damaged good. Maybe I should get myself checked out.\
Yuna. This is my first super yandere-focused show. This show is ALL about Yuna. Like, you can tell by just how much spotlight she has in the OP and EDs. You just don't really understand the extent of her involvement in the plot until the endgame. At first, I found Yuna to be a super intoxicating character. Yandere are entertaining, and she starts off a good one. Then, like everyone else, she is annoying for a majority of the show. Her actions are totally predictable and there's very little change in the types of situations she is put in. She is crazy, we get it. But you don't really get a sense for HOW crazy she is until the final act. The mysteries surrounding her life and the survival game really start to balloon, and this is what sets the pace for the ending episodes. From episodes ~19 and on, I quite like her character. She seems thoughtful, and the situations she is put in are more nuanced. I just wish she were less of a binary switch in the first 18 episodes. Her personality is entirely based on if she is alone with Yukki/if Yukki is in danger. It's a drag. I honestly would've liked to see more of her violent tendencies and for more fights.\
\
Enjoyment: 7 \
I feel like I've covered this in the other sections. Pretty much the first half was a drag, but the characters and intrigue pick up in the second act. Your first half should be good! Also, when the show tries to be an action thriller, which is often, it doesn't really succeed. Seriously, the visuals and pacing need more weight to them. A lot of the drama doesn't work either. But in the end, I'm glad to have watched it. The ending parts will give me something to think about for tomorrow. \
\
\
Overall: 6\
Well, that's that. I've been over pretty much everything I can think of. The biggest thing holding this down is the first act, but I really don't see this ever getting higher than a 7 from me, even if my enjoyment were more consistent. The elements of the work just aren't very cohesive and there are too many missed opportunities when trying to execute on tone and mood. Honestly, as I continue doing these reviews and reach peak jaded anime nerd, this is a series that I could see myself re-scoring as low as a 4, but I need more samples to be sure. \
Oh, and the little character samples after the credits are a neat idea. Not necessarily executed well in this show, but it's a cool idea that I would like to see more of.\
        ",
